The existing `useLongPress` hook at `apps/client/src/layers/shared/model/use-long-press.ts` uses touch events (`onTouchStart`, `onTouchEnd`, `onTouchMove`). The ResponsiveContextMenu needs pointer events instead (`onPointerDown`, `onPointerUp`, `onPointerLeave`, `onPointerCancel`) to work correctly with Vaul Drawer triggers on both touch and pointer devices.

Update the hook to use pointer events and add primary-button filtering.

**File to modify:** `apps/client/src/layers/shared/model/use-long-press.ts`

**Current implementation:**
```ts
import { useRef, useCallback } from 'react';
import { TIMING } from '@/layers/shared/lib';

interface UseLongPressOptions {
  ms?: number;
  onLongPress: () => void;
}

export function useLongPress({ onLongPress, ms = TIMING.LONG_PRESS_MS }: UseLongPressOptions) {
  const timerRef = useRef<number | null>(null);

  const onTouchStart = useCallback(() => {
    timerRef.current = window.setTimeout(onLongPress, ms);
  }, [onLongPress, ms]);

  const onTouchEnd = useCallback(() => {
    if (timerRef.current !== null) {
      clearTimeout(timerRef.current);
      timerRef.current = null;
    }
  }, []);

  return {
    onTouchStart,
    onTouchEnd,
    onTouchMove: onTouchEnd,
  };
}
```

**Updated implementation:**
```ts
import { useRef, useCallback } from 'react';
import { TIMING } from '@/layers/shared/lib';

interface UseLongPressOptions {
  /** Delay in ms before the long-press fires. Default: 500 (TIMING.LONG_PRESS_MS). */
  ms?: number;
  /** Called when long-press is detected. */
  onLongPress: () => void;
}

interface UseLongPressReturn {
  onPointerDown: (e: React.PointerEvent) => void;
  onPointerUp: () => void;
  onPointerLeave: () => void;
  onPointerCancel: () => void;
}

/** Return pointer event handlers that trigger a callback after a sustained press. */
export function useLongPress({ onLongPress, ms = TIMING.LONG_PRESS_MS }: UseLongPressOptions): UseLongPressReturn {
  const timerRef = useRef<number | null>(null);

  const clear = useCallback(() => {
    if (timerRef.current !== null) {
      clearTimeout(timerRef.current);
      timerRef.current = null;
    }
  }, []);

  const onPointerDown = useCallback(
    (e: React.PointerEvent) => {
      // Only fire on primary pointer (left click / single touch)
      if (e.button !== 0) return;
      timerRef.current = window.setTimeout(onLongPress, ms);
    },
    [onLongPress, ms]
  );

  return {
    onPointerDown,
    onPointerUp: clear,
    onPointerLeave: clear,
    onPointerCancel: clear,
  };
}
```

**Key changes:**
1. Replace `onTouchStart`/`onTouchEnd`/`onTouchMove` with `onPointerDown`/`onPointerUp`/`onPointerLeave`/`onPointerCancel`
2. Add `e.button !== 0` guard in `onPointerDown` to filter to primary pointer only
3. Add `UseLongPressReturn` interface for type safety
4. Extract shared `clear` callback to avoid repeating the clearTimeout logic
5. Update TSDoc to use `/** ... */` format

**Barrel file:** `apps/client/src/layers/shared/model/index.ts` already exports `useLongPress` on line 21, so no barrel change is needed.

**Check for other consumers:** Search the codebase for any existing consumers of the old touch-event API (`onTouchStart`, `onTouchEnd`, `onTouchMove`) and update them to use the new pointer-event API. If there are existing callers, they will need the same property name updates.

**Acceptance criteria:**
- `useLongPress` returns `{ onPointerDown, onPointerUp, onPointerLeave, onPointerCancel }`
- `onPointerDown` only starts timer for primary pointer (`e.button === 0`)
- Timer is cleared on `onPointerUp`, `onPointerLeave`, and `onPointerCancel`
- The `TIMING.LONG_PRESS_MS` default (500ms) is preserved
- No existing consumers are broken (update any if found)

Create a new shared UI primitive at `apps/client/src/layers/shared/ui/responsive-context-menu.tsx` that mirrors the pattern of the existing `responsive-dropdown-menu.tsx`. On desktop (`!useIsMobile()`), it delegates to Radix ContextMenu. On mobile, it uses a Vaul Drawer triggered by long-press via the `useLongPress` hook.

**New file:** `apps/client/src/layers/shared/ui/responsive-context-menu.tsx`

**Full implementation:**
```tsx
import * as React from 'react';
import { useIsMobile } from '../model';
import { useLongPress } from '../model';
import {
  ContextMenu,
  ContextMenuTrigger,
  ContextMenuContent,
  ContextMenuItem,
  ContextMenuSeparator,
} from './context-menu';
import { Drawer, DrawerContent, DrawerTrigger } from './drawer';
import { cn } from '../lib/utils';

// ── Context ──

const ResponsiveContextMenuContext = React.createContext<{
  isDesktop: boolean;
  close: () => void;
}>({
  isDesktop: true,
  close: () => {},
});

// ── Root ──

interface ResponsiveContextMenuProps {
  children: React.ReactNode;
}

/** Renders a context menu on desktop (right-click) or a drawer on mobile (long-press). */
function ResponsiveContextMenu({ children }: ResponsiveContextMenuProps) {
  const isDesktop = !useIsMobile();
  const [drawerOpen, setDrawerOpen] = React.useState(false);

  const close = React.useCallback(() => {
    setDrawerOpen(false);
  }, []);

  if (isDesktop) {
    return (
      <ResponsiveContextMenuContext.Provider value={{ isDesktop, close }}>
        <ContextMenu>{children}</ContextMenu>
      </ResponsiveContextMenuContext.Provider>
    );
  }

  return (
    <ResponsiveContextMenuContext.Provider value={{ isDesktop, close }}>
      <Drawer open={drawerOpen} onOpenChange={setDrawerOpen}>
        {children}
      </Drawer>
    </ResponsiveContextMenuContext.Provider>
  );
}

// ── Trigger ──

interface ResponsiveContextMenuTriggerProps {
  asChild?: boolean;
  children: React.ReactNode;
}

/** Trigger element — right-click on desktop, long-press on mobile. */
function ResponsiveContextMenuTrigger({ asChild, children }: ResponsiveContextMenuTriggerProps) {
  const { isDesktop, close } = React.useContext(ResponsiveContextMenuContext);

  if (isDesktop) {
    return <ContextMenuTrigger asChild={asChild}>{children}</ContextMenuTrigger>;
  }

  return <MobileTrigger asChild={asChild}>{children}</MobileTrigger>;
}

/** Mobile trigger that opens the drawer on long-press. */
function MobileTrigger({
  asChild,
  children,
}: {
  asChild?: boolean;
  children: React.ReactNode;
}) {
  // Access the drawer's open state setter through the context.
  // DrawerTrigger handles open/close, but we need long-press to open it.
  // We wrap with DrawerTrigger to let Vaul manage focus, then layer long-press on top.
  const longPressHandlers = useLongPress({
    onLongPress: () => {
      // Trigger will be found by the Drawer's onOpenChange
    },
  });

  // Vaul's DrawerTrigger already handles click-to-open. For long-press,
  // we intercept pointer events and programmatically open via context.
  return (
    <DrawerTrigger asChild={asChild} {...longPressHandlers}>
      {children}
    </DrawerTrigger>
  );
}

// ── Content ──

function ResponsiveContextMenuContent({
  className,
  children,
  ...props
}: React.ComponentPropsWithoutRef<typeof ContextMenuContent>) {
  const { isDesktop } = React.useContext(ResponsiveContextMenuContext);

  if (isDesktop) {
    return (
      <ContextMenuContent className={className} {...props}>
        {children}
      </ContextMenuContent>
    );
  }

  return (
    <DrawerContent>
      <div className="pb-6">{children}</div>
    </DrawerContent>
  );
}

// ── Item ──

function ResponsiveContextMenuItem({
  className,
  children,
  onClick,
  ...props
}: React.ComponentPropsWithoutRef<typeof ContextMenuItem>) {
  const { isDesktop, close } = React.useContext(ResponsiveContextMenuContext);

  if (isDesktop) {
    return (
      <ContextMenuItem className={className} onClick={onClick} {...props}>
        {children}
      </ContextMenuItem>
    );
  }

  return (
    <button
      type="button"
      className={cn(
        'border-border flex w-full items-center gap-3 border-b px-4 py-3 text-left text-sm transition-colors',
        'active:bg-accent/50 min-h-[44px]',
        'last:border-b-0',
        className
      )}
      onClick={(e) => {
        onClick?.(e as unknown as React.MouseEvent<HTMLDivElement>);
        close();
      }}
    >
      {children}
    </button>
  );
}

// ── Separator ──

function ResponsiveContextMenuSeparator({
  className,
  ...props
}: React.ComponentPropsWithoutRef<typeof ContextMenuSeparator>) {
  const { isDesktop } = React.useContext(ResponsiveContextMenuContext);

  if (isDesktop) {
    return <ContextMenuSeparator className={className} {...props} />;
  }

  // On mobile, items already have border-b — separator is a no-op.
  return null;
}

export {
  ResponsiveContextMenu,
  ResponsiveContextMenuTrigger,
  ResponsiveContextMenuContent,
  ResponsiveContextMenuItem,
  ResponsiveContextMenuSeparator,
};
```

**Design decisions:**
1. Follows the exact structure of `responsive-dropdown-menu.tsx` — same `ResponsiveContextMenuContext` pattern with `{ isDesktop, close }`
2. Desktop path: pure delegation to Radix ContextMenu (right-click trigger)
3. Mobile path: Vaul Drawer with `DrawerTrigger` that receives long-press handlers from `useLongPress`
4. Mobile items are full-width buttons with min-height 44px (WCAG 2.5.5 touch target)
5. Mobile items auto-close the drawer after click via `close()`
6. Mobile separator is a no-op since items already have `border-b`
7. The `MobileTrigger` component wraps `DrawerTrigger` to spread long-press pointer handlers onto it

**Important implementation note:** The `MobileTrigger` needs careful attention. `DrawerTrigger` from Vaul opens on click by default. For long-press-to-open behavior, you may need to prevent the default click handler on `DrawerTrigger` and instead open programmatically from the `useLongPress` callback. Test this carefully — if `DrawerTrigger` opens on click, that might be acceptable UX (tap opens on mobile), but the spec calls for long-press. Consider either:
- Option A: Use `DrawerTrigger` as-is (click opens on mobile, which is common UX), and long-press also opens
- Option B: Skip `DrawerTrigger` entirely, use a plain `div` with long-press handlers that calls `setDrawerOpen(true)` through context

Go with Option A unless testing reveals issues — having both click and long-press is acceptable mobile UX.

**Acceptance criteria:**
- On desktop (viewport >= 768px), right-click opens the context menu
- On mobile (viewport < 768px), long-press opens a bottom drawer
- Menu items call their `onClick` handlers and close the menu/drawer
- Mobile items have min-height 44px per WCAG 2.5.5
- The component renders nothing extra when used as a wrapper (no visual impact when menu is closed)
- All five components are exported: `ResponsiveContextMenu`, `ResponsiveContextMenuTrigger`, `ResponsiveContextMenuContent`, `ResponsiveContextMenuItem`, `ResponsiveContextMenuSeparator`

